    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-10-02T01:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-10-02T01:00:00-05:00" n="612"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d612">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">693.003/447: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Reinsch</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-10-02T14:00:00+08:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 2, 1917, 2 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[<hi rend="italic">Received October 2, 9.60 a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your instructions September 20, 4 p.m.<note n="63" xml:id="d612fn63">
                        <ref target="frus1917Supp02v01#pg_689">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1917, Supplement 2, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 689</ref>.</note> are understood to the
                    effect that if the Chinese Government withholds the payment of the Boxer
                    indemnity during the period stated no objection will be made by the American
                    Government on the condition specified.</p>
                <p>The Chinese Government has proposed the assembling of an international commission
                    at Shanghai for the purpose of revising the specific tariff to yield 5 per cent
                    effective as provided by the treaties. I beg to suggest that a commission be
                    designated and that the Commercial Attaché possesses the necessary knowledge of
                    the situation.</p>
                <p>Also I beg to query whether or not, as the recomputation of the 5 per cent
                    effective is in essence an administrative act, the consent of the Senate to the
                    determinations of the commission will be required.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Reinsch</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
